{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: A unit test of only the sort helper can miss failures in discovery/parsing/wiring to execution. REAL-INFRA: no subprocess or external service is required; local filesystem + local Postgres is enough. MOCK-HIDE: mocking DB execution could hide mis-ordered real execution flow. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: not applicable.","test_description":"Create a temp migrations directory with out-of-order filenames (e.g., 002.sql, 010.sql, 001.sql) where each migration inserts its version into an audit table. Run the runner once against a local test Postgres DB and assert inserted order is 001, 002, 010 and that _migrations records the same order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: idempotency depends on persisted _migrations state plus real runner logic across runs; pure unit mocks can miss schema/query mismatches. REAL-INFRA: local DB/filesystem suffices. MOCK-HIDE: mocked metadata reads/writes may always pass and hide duplicate execution bugs. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: not applicable.","test_description":"Use a migration with a visible side effect (e.g., insert one row into marker table). Run runner twice against same local Postgres DB. Assert marker row count is still 1 after second run and _migrations contains one record for that version.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run